John Panzer  wrote:

&gt;
&gt; Atom has defined both feed and entry resources.  A feed document can 
&gt; aggregate multiple entries together -- indeed this is the purpose of
&gt; its existence (to aggregate, order, and potentially filter).  A GET
&gt; on an individual entry resource gives the entry&#39;s Atom representation
&gt; of course.  A GET on a related feed gets that entry, plus its
&gt; &#39;sibling&#39; entries.  This is all based on the definition of the feed
&gt; itself of course.
&gt; 
&gt; Question:  Is this fundamentally different from the DELETE case
&gt; below? If so, how?
&gt;

Yes, because GET doesn&#39;t have side effects, DELETE does.  When I GET a
collection, I receive links to the individual members, so if my client
wants to delete all of those members, it has the URIs over which to
iterate a bunch of DELETE requests.

-Eric

